# Public Site — Documentation

The patient-facing website for Lebeza Psychiatry Consultation — React + Vite single-page app. No authentication; every page is publicly accessible.

## Tech stack
- **React** (function components + hooks), **React Router**
- **Vite** as the build tool/dev server
- **Axios** for API calls (`services/api.js`)
- Utility-class styling (same visual system as the admin panel)

## Environment variables
| Variable | Purpose | Default |
|---|---|---|
| `VITE_API_BASE_URL` | Base URL of the backend API | `http://localhost:5001/api` |

## Folder structure
```
src/
├── App.jsx                  Route definitions (all wrapped in the shared Layout)
├── components/
│   ├── layout/               Navbar, Footer, Layout (shared header/footer shell)
│   ├── home/                  Homepage sections: Hero, About, Services, Doctors, Stats bar, Trusted-by
│   ├── doctors/                DoctorCard, DoctorDetail
│   ├── services/               ServiceCard, ServiceDetail
│   ├── news/                    NewsCard, NewsDetail
│   ├── projects/                PartnersSection
│   ├── booking/                  BookingForm, BookingConfirmation
│   └── ui/                        Generic building blocks: Button, Input, Select, Textarea, Modal, LoadingSpinner, SectionLabel/Title, StatCard
├── pages/                      One component per route (see table below)
├── services/                   One API-wrapper module per resource (doctorService, serviceService, appointmentService, branchService, departmentService, inquiryService, newsService)
├── hooks/                       useFetch (generic GET hook), useAppointmentForm, useInquiryForm
└── utils/                        constants.js (nav links, clinic info, time slots), formatDate.js, validators.js
```

## Routes
| Path | Component | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `/` | `HomePage` | Hero, about, services preview, doctors preview, stats, trusted-by |
| `/services` | `ServicesPage` | Full services list |
| `/services/:slug` | `ServiceDetailPage` | Single service detail |
| `/about` | `AboutPage` | About / mission / values / vision |
| `/doctors` | `DoctorsPage` | Doctor directory |
| `/doctors/:id` | `DoctorDetailPage` | Single doctor profile |
| `/projects` | `ProjectsPage` | Projects/partners |
| `/contact` | `ContactPage` | Contact info + inquiry form |
| `/book` | `BookingPage` | Appointment booking form |
| `*` | `NotFoundPage` | 404 |

## Data flow
- All pages fetch through the shared `services/api.js` Axios instance, which points at `VITE_API_BASE_URL` and normalizes a few shorthand env-var formats (e.g. a bare `:5001` becomes `http://localhost:5001`).
- Most page content (page headers, hero copy, etc.) comes from the backend's `/content/:page` endpoint — the **same data the admin panel's Web Editor writes to**. This is what lets the admin's Web Editor preview show real, live site content in an iframe.
- Doctors/Services/Branches data comes from their respective public `GET` endpoints (no auth required for reads).
- The **Booking** page and the **Contact** page submit to `POST /appointments` and `POST /inquiries` respectively — both public, unauthenticated endpoints. Submitted inquiries show up in the admin panel's Contact Messages page (gated there by the `view_contact_messages` permission); submitted appointments show up in the admin panel's Appointments page (gated by `view_appointments`/`manage_appointments`).

## Content editing relationship with the Admin panel
This site has **no admin UI of its own** — everything editable (page headers/copy, doctors, services, branches) is managed from the separate Admin Panel project and simply rendered here. If a page looks wrong or out of date, the fix is almost always in the Admin Panel's Web Editor or the relevant resource page (Doctors/Services/Branches), not in this project's code — unless it's a layout/styling/structural issue, which does live here.

## Running locally
1. `npm install`
2. Set `VITE_API_BASE_URL` in a `.env` file if the backend isn't running on the default `http://localhost:5001/api`.
3. `npm run dev` — starts the Vite dev server (default port 5173; note this is the same default port the Admin Panel's Web Editor preview points at via its own `VITE_SITE_URL`, so make sure only one of the two projects is actually serving on 5173 when testing the live preview).
